# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# .env  —  Notion to iCal Sync  —  SECRET CONFIGURATION
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# ⚠️  NEVER commit this file to git or share it with anyone.
#     It is already listed in .gitignore for your protection.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Your Notion Internal Integration Token.
# Get it from: https://www.notion.so/my-integrations
# It starts with "secret_"
NOTION_TOKEN=secret_REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_TOKEN_HERE

# Where your .ics files will be saved on your Mac.
# Apple Calendar will subscribe to files in this folder.
# You can change this path — just make sure the folder exists (the script creates it).
OUTPUT_DIR=/Users/REPLACE_WITH_YOUR_MAC_USERNAME/NotionCalendars

# Your Notion databases as a JSON array.
# Each entry needs:
#   "id"   — the database ID (explained in the setup guide)
#   "name" — what you want the calendar to be called in Apple Calendar
#
# Example with two databases:
NOTION_DATABASES=[{"id":"REPLACE_WITH_DATABASE_ID_1","name":"Work Projects"},{"id":"REPLACE_WITH_DATABASE_ID_2","name":"Personal Tasks"}]

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# To add more databases, just add more entries to the JSON array above:
# [
#   {"id":"abc123","name":"Work Projects"},
#   {"id":"def456","name":"Personal Tasks"},
#   {"id":"ghi789","name":"Content Calendar"}
# ]
# (Keep it on one line in the .env file, or use the format above as reference)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
